Here is the strict, command-level audit of the Bazzite Unified Home Server + Gaming Station Guide.

The guide demonstrates an exceptionally high level of technical rigor. It successfully navigates complex interactions between immutable file systems (Fedora Atomic/rpm-ostree), Wayland compositor constraints, systemd session management, and SELinux policies. The solutions provided for common Linux pitfalls (e.g., systemd cgroup reaping, blind mount vulnerabilities, SDDM config merging) are elegant, secure, and fully deterministic.

Every phase transitions the system logically. There are no circular dependencies, and the teardown/recovery paths are cleanly accounted for. Everything included in the guide is classified as essential; there is no fluff or unnecessary configuration.

However, the audit identified a few issues regarding proxy constraints, alignment, and implicit environment assumptions.

🚨 Issues Identified & Classifications

[Critical] - None found.
The guide contains no catastrophic errors, insecure defaults, or commands that will break the system state. Execution is safe, and dependencies are correctly ordered.

[Major] - Missing Nginx Proxy Manager (NPM) Advanced Configuration

Issue: In Phase 10, Step 2, the guide sets up NPM to route traffic to nextcloud-aio-apache. However, it fails to instruct the user to add client_max_body_size 0; and proxy timeout overrides in NPM's Advanced tab.

Consequence: NPM defaults to a restrictive payload size. Any attempt to upload large files (e.g., >1GB) via the Nextcloud Web UI will fail with an HTTP 413 Payload Too Large error. (Note: Desktop/mobile clients use chunked uploads and will survive, but the web interface will break).

Fix: Add an explicit instruction in Phase 10 to paste client_max_body_size 0; proxy_read_timeout 36000s; proxy_send_timeout 36000s; into the NPM proxy host's Advanced configuration.

[Minor] - parted Drive Alignment Syntax

Issue: Phase 6 uses sudo parted "$DATA_DRIVE" --script mkpart primary ext4 0% 100%.

Consequence: While modern parted usually interprets 0% as the start of the optimal alignment boundary (typically 1MiB), using 0% can historically cause misaligned sectors on certain NVMe/SSD controllers, degrading write performance.

Fix: Change to mkpart primary ext4 1MiB 100% to mathematically guarantee optimal sector alignment across all hardware.

[Minor] - Unstated Privilege Escalation via Docker Group

Issue: Phase 5 includes sudo usermod -aG docker $USER.

Consequence: Adding a user to the docker group grants passwordless root-equivalent access to the system (as a user can spawn a privileged container and mount the host root filesystem).

Fix: While the guide tightly secures SSH access (making the perimeter highly secure), the hidden assumption that $USER is now effectively root should be explicitly documented in the security notes.

[Minor] - Hardcoded Timezone Risks

Issue: Phase 7 Compose files include - TZ=Europe/Berlin with an inline comment to change it.

Consequence: Users executing copy-paste blindly will end up with containers running in Central European Time. This causes Nextcloud cron jobs, logs, and calendar events to exhibit timezone skew.

Fix: Instruct the user to verify their TZ database name (e.g., via timedatectl) before pasting the compose files.

✅ Final Validation Checklist

This checklist verifies that the system has achieved the exact intended end-state through purely observable outputs. No assumptions are relied upon.

1. OS & Kernel Validation

Run rpm-ostree status. Verify docker-ce is listed under LayeredPackages.

Run systemctl status sleep.target. Verify the state explicitly says masked.

2. Security & Network Perimeter

Run sudo semanage port -l | grep ssh. Output must explicitly include tcp 53222.

Run sudo firewall-cmd --list-all. Verify ports: 53222/tcp is present and 22/tcp, 80/tcp, 443/tcp, and 3389/tcp are absent.

Run sudo fail2ban-client status sshd. Verify the jail is active and monitoring the custom port.

3. Storage & Integrity Validation

Unmount the data drive temporarily: sudo umount /srv/nextcloud-data.

Attempt to create a file: touch /srv/nextcloud-data/test. Must fail with Permission denied (verifying the chattr +i blind-mount guard is active).

Remount the drive: sudo mount -a.

Run ls -Zd /srv/nextcloud-data. Output must show the SELinux context system_u:object_r:container_file_t:s0.

4. Docker & Services

Run docker ps. Verify nextcloud-aio-mastercontainer, nginx-proxy-manager, and duckdns are showing Up.

Execute an external DNS lookup: nslookup yourname.duckdns.org 8.8.8.8. Output must resolve to your public home IP address.

Disconnect from local Wi-Fi, use cellular, and navigate to https://yourname.duckdns.org. Nextcloud login screen must load with a valid SSL certificate.

5. Session Script & Systemd Escape Validation

Connect via SSH. Run sudo start-kde.sh. Ensure the command prompt returns immediately without hanging.

Check loginctl list-sessions. Verify a seat0 session exists for plasma.

Terminate your SSH connection entirely. Wait 15 seconds. Reconnect via SSH.

Run cat /etc/sddm.conf.d/zzz-headless-server.conf. The file must contain empty User= and Session= variables, proving the systemd-run transient unit successfully escaped the SSH cgroup termination and restored the headless state.

🏆 Rating Score

9.5 / 10

This is an exceptionally well-engineered guide. The author deeply understands Fedora Atomic's limitations, Wayland's hardware constraints, and systemd's behavior. The use of systemd-run --collect to escape SSH cgroup reaping, combined with the immutable directory trick (chattr +i) to prevent Docker from corrupting the root file system on mount failure, is brilliant system administration. The deduction of 0.5 points is solely for the missing Nginx Proxy Manager large-file upload configuration, which would break standard cloud storage functionality for end-users.
